story.text: Residuality theory models software systems as interconnected residues—an alternative to component and process modeling that uses applied complexity science to make managing uncertainty a fundamental part of the design process. Residuality Theory by Barry O’Reilly @ Jfokus 2022 [https://www.jfokus.se/jfokus22-preso/Residuality-Theory.pdf pdf] [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96IqczEd88A youtube]

YOUTUBE 96IqczEd88A
Residuality Theory by Barry O’Reilly @ Jfokus 2022  [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96IqczEd88A youtube]
# Architecture Problem

We create a small, ordered, structured, simple, innocent piece of software and then put it into a dynamic, constantly evolving, changing environment which has people and businesses and society and economics and politics. Quite a number of things pop up that we didn't understand could even exist.

A rough oval representing the messy reality. A small box with a small network of smaller boxes representing the designed system. Several Xs representing stressors that we cannot predict nor control, drawn within the oval and outside the box with arrows pointing from each X towards the box.

The way we cope with the messy environment is to draw a smaller circle around our software to make the problem easier to manage. We use well-meaning tools like requirements engineering. We force stakeholders to be really precise else we ignore them. We use things like risk management—we say this has a low probability of happening so we'll ignore it, or this has a very low impact so we ignore that too. As soon as we put this into production another X pops up, outside our considered environment.

A box containing a small network of five other boxes representing the software is surrounded by an oval with a few Xs between the box and the oval—the oval represents a subset of the messy environment which we are willing to consider for our design. The smaller oval is surrounded by a larger oval with other Xs. One X is drawn in red representing a problem that happens in production that was outside our design consideration and nevertheless disrupts our software.

This is our problem with architecture—how do we design structures for a bunch of Xs that are going to pop up all the time when we don't know what they are, we don't know where they come from, and we don't know how they're going to impact us?
A good number of architects, a good number of software engineers are able to do this.

Reflective Practitioner by Donald Schön 1983. Most professionals in complex environments develop reflective practice: use a gut feeling to make decisions that are more or less correct. But our culture is bound to an idea of technical rationality. We believe we should be working in a structured analytic way. Gut feeling is never really accepted. See also Reflective Practice [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflective_practice wikipedia]
We'll look at a few concepts from complexity theory.
# Random Simulation [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=439 7m19s]
We can estimate the area of an unknown circle inside a known square by picking random points and counting which fall inside the circle and which fall outside.

Circle inscribed inside a square with sides of length X. Dots placed randomly. Equation (x*x/2) showing area of the circle is half the area of the square. Estimate the area of an unknown circle inside a known square by picking random points and counting which fall inside the circle and which fall outside.

When we do requirements engineering, risk management, we're actually doing random simulation but we've convinced ourselves that we're actually doing something really thoughtful and analytical and logical. But we're not. If we threw darts at a dartboard the results would be fairly similar. That offends some people.
# Kauffman Network [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=582 9m42s]

A boolean network where the number of states in the network is 2^N. Kauffman used 100,000 nodes. When he linked nodes into a dependency graph, the number of states fell massively to the square root of N—about 317 states for 100,000 nodes. Kauffman called these states attractors.

This fundamental finding in the complexity sciences is how we survive. In a world with millions of things all moving at the same time, they constrain and restrict each other to reduce the number of possible states.
That's the only way as humans that we could ever navigate something as complex as a city or a forest.
# NKP Analysis [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=745 12m25s]
N is the number of nodes in the network. Keep this number low.

K is the number of connections for the most connected node in the network. When K is equal to 2 everything is nice and stable. The same attractors are visited all the time and the system arrives at its attractors very quickly.
P is bias. We take the function of one of these nodes and give it a much higher probability of returning a certain result.

In software engineering and software architecture we bias our nodes by using things like schema, contract, validation, error handling, flow control. We bias our nodes so it does roughly the similar thing all the time.
# General Theory of Software Engineering [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=853 14m13s]
Two step process: 1) random simulation of the environment, 2) NKP analysis—keep n and k low and reduce p as much as possible in order to keep order in the software system.
General Theory of Software Engingeering is a two step process: 1) random simulation, and 2) NKP analysis.
# Residuality Theory [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=955 15m55s]
Make random simulation more random. Make NKP analysis explicit.
# Attractor Network [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=975 16m15s]

The insight from Kauffman Networks tells us that there will be a number of attractors and the system is going to constantly arrive back at those attractors. The problem space is smaller than what we thought.

There is a network of attractors. The things that makes the system shift is still Xs—unexpected events in the business environment pushes the system from one attractor to another. Our architecture either continues to work or it falls over completely and has to be rebuilt.

Architects with a lot of experience tend to build software systems that respond to a lot of different attractors. Junior architects tend to build systems that respond to one happy path attractor which they learned about when the asked for requirements.
# Residue [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=1086 18m6s]
A residue is how we capture this idea of an attractor in our architectures.
Start the design from the happy path attractor. Develop a naive architecture—naive because we haven't explored it very much.

Think about a form of stress that could pop up in this environment. This is our random simulation which reveals a new attractor. A competitor drops their price. Or the market changes its mind about our product. Something on the business level.
We change our architecture so that it survives this particular attractor. We do this many times until we come up with an architecture that can survive these many attractors in the network.
We find that one residue will survive many attractors. We can leverage the mathematics of networks.

A box labeled R on the left representing a residue. Arrows drawn from that box to four blobs to its right representing attractors. Each attractor with lines to five Xs further right representing disruptions. One X is circled. We only need one X to identify an attractor and a residue that survives that attractor in order to build a system that is robust against the entire disruptive tree.
# The Curse of High Dimensionality [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=1273 21m13s]

In our design thinking we are not random enough. Playfully begin your architecture with the hazard of a giant, fire-breathing lizard destroying Stockholm. If your architecture can survive the fire-breathing lizard, it can survive civil unrest, or a pandemic, or a war, or an invasion, or a cyber attack, or countless things we normally dismiss as too unlikely to consider in our designs.

This one silly, little, irrelevant, nonsense X with a probability very close to zero gives me protection against a whole bunch of other stuff that I'm not going to be able to predict or control or maybe even think about or see in these complex social systems.
# Residual Architecture [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=1397 23m17s]

What we end up with is a residual architecture that includes the naive architecture and many similar residues that descend from it in a network. What we need to do now is boil this network down into a single coherent architecture because we don't want to build this many things.
# Example: car charging system [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=1509 15m9s]
A compelling story about a design which survived unexpected political behaviors, among other things.
# Hyperliminal System [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=1914 31m54s]

Software architects are charged with building structured, ordered core within a disordered, disorganized, unpredictable environment. To design hyperliminal systems, the architect must constantly move between the structured, ordered world where our educations have well prepared us and the disordered, weird, unpredictable, uncontrollable world for which we have no preparation.
# Hyperliminal Coupling [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=2082 34m42s]

Non-functional requirements are revealed when we have unrelated systems which are coupled to each other through a stressor. The typical architecture diagram reveals no connection between these components. It turns out there are many such couplings and this web of invisible connections represents an accurate, and real-world picture of non-functional requirements.
# Contagion Analysis [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=2082 36m14s]
Adjacency matrix for dependencies between information flows between people and components. Reflection across the diagonal indicates interdependence between flows.

Then use an incidence matrix to apply our list of stressors to the list of information flows or functions. We put a one if that stressor affects that flow, otherwise a zero. Summing the columns and rows in this matrix allows prioritization of stressors and identification of which flows are most vulnerable.
We can discover non-functional requirements during analysis when flows that are coupled in the incidence matrix are independent of each other in the adjacency matrix.
With these areas identified we can return to our classical systems engineering tools to compose a design and components around these insights.
# Empirical Proof [https://youtu.be/96IqczEd88A?t=2440 40m40s]

We can design our naive architecture and a residual architecture against half of our list of stressors. This is stealing a trick from machine learning. We can then analyze our design against the second half of our stressors, comparing how the naive architecture would perform against our assessment of the residual architecture against those stressors. This is a simulation of our architecture coping with unknown unknowns.
I find this story resonates with wisdom from Fred Hebert's experience in Erlang.

story.title: Crash-Restart Patterns
story.text: Fred Hebert writes, Over the years I found that a similar pattern makes a lot of sense for Erlang processes that need to do crash-restart patterns, with the idea of "rolling back to a known stable state". In Erlang and elixir, specifically with OTP, we have access to these architectural patterns that most languages only have when you're dealing with hardware machines or virtual machines and not within the language itself. See the second half of The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Unexpected
